    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-07-21T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-07-21T16:00:00-05:00" n="139"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d139">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">835.6363/437: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Argentina</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Cox</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Buenos Aires</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-07-21T17:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 21, 1936—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 8 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>144. Embassy’s despatch 1061 [<hi rend="italic">1161</hi>] of April 29<note
                        n="21" xml:id="d139fn21">Not printed.</note> and subsequent. Executive
                        decree<note n="22" xml:id="d139fn22">Decree 86,639 of July 20, 1936,
                        published in <hi rend="italic">La Nación</hi>, July 21.</note> published
                    today prohibits exportation and limits as from August 5 next importation of
                    petroleum and liquid hydrocarbons under what, in effect, is a license system
                    determined and operated by the YPF,<note n="23" xml:id="d139fn23">Yacimientos
                        Petrolíferos Fiscales (Argentine State Oilfields).</note> the Government
                    owned oil administration. Local heads of Standard Oil Company and Texas Company
                    inform me that decree will have far-reaching effect on their importations of
                    crude oil, roughly estimated in the case of Standard at 40 per cent and in the
                    case of Texas at practically 100 per cent. I understand Standard Oil Company is
                    consulting with the British oil companies here with a view to joint action
                    through legal channels. Resume of decree as published in today’s press being
                    forwarded by air mail tonight.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cox</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
